<P>
SHELL: NOTHING TAINTED ABOUT VICTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS DUFRESNE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Coach Art Shell said Monday's victory wasn't tainted because Miami was playing 
without receivers Mark Clayton, Freddie Banks and fullback Tony Paige. 
</P>
<P>
"We didn't make excuses when we lost people," Shell said. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't feel sorry for them." 
</P>
<P>
Shell couldn't have been happier with his team's numbers against Miami: The 
Raiders rushed for a season-high 177 yards and yielded a season-low 14 yards 
rushing on defense. The Raider pass rush sacked Dan Marino twice and kept 
consistent pressure on him, but the Raider offensive line did not allow a sack 
of quarterback Jay Schroeder. 
</P>
<P>
"The whole thing was impressive," Shell said. "The whole team came out and 
played, not just the defense." 
</P>
<P>
Shell on the possibility of signing defensive end Dexter Manley: "To be 
truthful, we haven't discussed Manley." . . . Bo Jackson reported a sore neck 
Tuesday and fullback Napoleon McCallum cracked a bone in his wrist on a 
kickoff. CHRIS DUFRESNE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
